00:03:29,934 --> 00:03:31,115
So what's on the menu today?

79
00:03:31,456 --> 00:03:33,578
So we'll talk about our speech recognition pipeline

80
00:03:33,899 --> 00:03:36,301
and then the decision making with the emotional components

81
00:03:36,562 --> 00:03:38,063
and some factual statement at the end.

82
00:03:39,896 --> 00:03:42,357
So let's start with speech recognition and pipeline.

83
00:03:42,957 --> 00:03:45,338
So the first block is our speech recognition engine.

84
00:03:45,358 --> 00:03:49,260
It's taking the voice and translating it

85
00:03:49,320 --> 00:03:51,941
into a sentence or a list of predicated words

86
00:03:51,961 --> 00:03:52,821
with their part of speech.

87
00:03:53,661 --> 00:03:56,302
And we are sending this data to our game experience

88
00:03:56,522 --> 00:03:57,503
through the voice pipeline.

89
00:03:59,023 --> 00:04:00,544
And the first block is a grammar parser.

90
00:04:02,076 --> 00:04:04,437
And here the goal is to translate this language-based

91
00:04:04,497 --> 00:04:07,117
grammar into our ontology-based grammar.

92
00:04:07,398 --> 00:04:10,338
So you can see some new types, such as predicates and

93
00:04:10,498 --> 00:04:14,480
object, which is much more easily understood by our AI.

94
00:04:16,240 --> 00:04:18,461
And then we have a word abstraction step, where the

95
00:04:18,481 --> 00:04:21,082
goal is to translate these words into a language

96
00:04:21,222 --> 00:04:22,462
independent representation.

97
00:04:23,242 --> 00:04:25,083
And here it's a colored block you can see here.

98
00:04:26,578 --> 00:04:27,999
So why do we want to do that?

99
00:04:28,419 --> 00:04:30,761
Well, we want to support multiple languages

100
00:04:31,001 --> 00:04:33,122
without limiting the player set of vocabulary.

101
00:04:33,762 --> 00:04:36,284
So if later I want to add French to another language,

102
00:04:36,524 --> 00:04:39,926
I don't want to do all the bindings one by one manually.

103
00:04:40,406 --> 00:04:43,167
It's too much work, and I want a better way to do that,

104
00:04:43,187 --> 00:04:44,928
a method that is maybe automated.

105
00:04:47,150 --> 00:04:50,271
The main problem here is that worlds are language-based,

106
00:04:50,711 --> 00:04:53,633
so they don't have binding one-to-one between languages.

107
00:04:54,273 --> 00:04:55,294
So we need to abstract them.

108
00:04:57,409 --> 00:05:00,791
And the idea here was to create the DNA of a word,

109
00:05:01,091 --> 00:05:03,732
in this case, thinking about what could be the genes.

110
00:05:05,433 --> 00:05:08,695
So if I say, take an apple, or take a break,

111
00:05:09,215 --> 00:05:11,276
these two take has different meaning.

112
00:05:12,277 --> 00:05:13,898
So you could actually have your word take

113
00:05:14,278 --> 00:05:16,679
and tag it with all the different meaning it has.

114
00:05:17,540 --> 00:05:19,141
And one meaning could be one gene,

115
00:05:19,841 --> 00:05:22,722
and then the DNA will be just a list of meanings.

116
00:05:23,983 --> 00:05:26,625
So with that idea, we decided to use WordNet.

117
00:05:27,841 --> 00:05:31,242
A database of set of creative synonyms named Synset.

118
00:05:31,782 --> 00:05:33,342
It's expressing a distinct concept.

119
00:05:34,463 --> 00:05:36,723
And it's about multiple languages, which is what we want.

120
00:05:38,484 --> 00:05:39,524
So let's take an example.

121
00:05:40,184 --> 00:05:42,404
Let's say that we want to create a concept of big

122
00:05:42,444 --> 00:05:45,225
in our experience, as in a big apple.

123
00:05:46,065 --> 00:05:46,946
So an adjective here.

124
00:05:47,926 --> 00:05:49,806
At first, we search in our database

125
00:05:50,506 --> 00:05:52,047
what are the different meaning of big.

126
00:05:52,287 --> 00:05:52,987
We have maybe 20.

127
00:05:54,767 --> 00:05:57,108
but it's too much, so which big meaning

128
00:05:57,168 --> 00:05:58,548
are we actually interested in?

129
00:05:59,688 --> 00:06:02,069
So we said an adjective, so let's remove the adverbs.

130
00:06:03,809 --> 00:06:06,050
And then we're going to take all the meaning one by one

131
00:06:06,370 --> 00:06:07,950
and select the one that we're interested in.

132
00:06:08,850 --> 00:06:12,271
In this case, we're interested in above average in size

133
00:06:12,371 --> 00:06:16,572
or number or quantity or extent, and also significant.

134
00:06:17,672 --> 00:06:20,493
And these two meanings will make our DNA

135
00:06:20,573 --> 00:06:22,433
for the concept of big we wanted to create.

136
00:06:24,808 --> 00:06:27,268
If we have some doubt about one of this meaning,

137
00:06:27,508 --> 00:06:30,009
we can check the WordNet database in detail

138
00:06:30,229 --> 00:06:33,770
and understand which words they are actually bound to

139
00:06:34,530 --> 00:06:36,171
in the different languages it supports.

140
00:06:37,171 --> 00:06:40,031
And we also have sentences examples at the bottom.

141
00:06:41,532 --> 00:06:42,852
So it's very easy to understand

142
00:06:43,032 --> 00:06:44,653
if this meaning is the one you want.

143
00:06:47,493 --> 00:06:47,693
Okay.

144
00:06:48,905 --> 00:06:52,548
So now our statement is totally language independent,

145
00:06:53,148 --> 00:06:55,710
and we are supporting multiple languages thanks to WordNet.

146
00:06:57,131 --> 00:07:01,714
And also, now that I'm on the previous one, yes, this one.

147
00:07:02,794 --> 00:07:04,996
So now, the goal will be to try to understand

148
00:07:05,056 --> 00:07:08,378
this abstracted world into the concept

149
00:07:08,418 --> 00:07:10,500
that we're actually supporting in our game world.

150
00:07:12,187 --> 00:07:16,368
For instance, pickup and enormous are not part of our game,

151
00:07:16,789 --> 00:07:18,690
but we have take and we have big as well.

152
00:07:19,070 --> 00:07:21,311
And because they are close to pickup and enormous,

153
00:07:21,811 --> 00:07:24,672
our grounding step will be able to translate them

154
00:07:24,812 --> 00:07:25,733
into take and big.

155
00:07:32,076 --> 00:07:34,537
So here we are going to use a UTT-based scoring method.

156
00:07:35,817 --> 00:07:36,898
So here is a simple one.

157
00:07:37,398 --> 00:07:39,299
We have the word enormous with its DNA.

158
00:07:40,658 --> 00:07:43,420
And we have a list of predicates that we are supporting in our game world.

159
00:07:43,760 --> 00:07:46,722
So big, small, red, with their own DNA.

160
00:07:47,682 --> 00:07:49,384
And we are just going to compare their DNA

161
00:07:49,844 --> 00:07:53,026
and check which DNA is the closest to the DNA of Enormous.

162
00:07:54,127 --> 00:07:56,248
In this case, big is going to be the closest,

163
00:07:56,868 --> 00:07:58,589
so Enormous is going to become big.

164
00:07:59,570 --> 00:08:03,012
So now, if I say, for instance, take a giant apple,

165
00:08:03,513 --> 00:08:05,594
giant will also be translated into big.

166
00:08:06,655 --> 00:08:10,257
So we are actually now extending the player set of vocabulary.

167
00:08:11,387 --> 00:08:13,350
And we are also supporting multiple languages.

168
00:08:14,372 --> 00:08:16,615
So now we don't even know, actually, how many words

169
00:08:16,635 --> 00:08:17,496
we are supporting now.

170
00:08:20,533 --> 00:08:23,374
However, here we are still outside of our AI.

171
00:08:23,614 --> 00:08:25,075
We are just in our voice pipeline.

172
00:08:25,995 --> 00:08:27,756
So we cannot ground everything.

173
00:08:28,576 --> 00:08:31,757
Objects particularly relies on the knowledge of each agent.

174
00:08:32,197 --> 00:08:33,457
For instance, on the left,

175
00:08:34,037 --> 00:08:37,378
agent A known about a bowl, a banana, and a table.

176
00:08:37,979 --> 00:08:39,559
So if I say, take a fridge,

177
00:08:39,919 --> 00:08:42,400
it will try to understand the DNA of fridge

178
00:08:42,680 --> 00:08:45,741
against a bowl, or a banana, or a table.

179
00:08:45,981 --> 00:08:47,581
It doesn't know yet what is a fridge.

180
00:08:49,032 --> 00:08:50,313
So we'll do it later.

181
00:08:50,333 --> 00:08:54,955
Okay, so now our statement is ready.

182
00:08:55,095 --> 00:08:56,796
So we just store it in our statement memory

183
00:08:57,016 --> 00:08:58,157
and we can move to the next step,

184
00:08:59,998 --> 00:09:01,118
which is the decision making.

185
00:09:02,419 --> 00:09:04,760
So our decision making system is very simple.

186
00:09:04,780 --> 00:09:06,461
We have a goal manager and a planner.

187
00:09:07,581 --> 00:09:09,442
And the goal manager is UTT based.

188
00:09:10,623 --> 00:09:11,803
So we have a list of goals

189
00:09:12,464 --> 00:09:14,305
and we are going to compute a score for each of them.

190
00:09:14,985 --> 00:09:16,866
And we are going to execute the highest scored one.

191
00:09:17,929 --> 00:09:19,590
In this case, going to be listen to player.

192
00:09:20,270 --> 00:09:22,051
And the plan that we are going to have is listen,

193
00:09:22,752 --> 00:09:24,613
which will just copy the statement

194
00:09:24,833 --> 00:09:27,355
from the statement memory into the AI memory.

195
00:09:28,756 --> 00:09:30,177
And then the agent can decide

196
00:09:30,237 --> 00:09:32,779
if he want to execute or not this order.

197
00:09:33,820 --> 00:09:35,200
In this case, he does want to.

198
00:09:36,321 --> 00:09:37,462
So we are going to have a plan

199
00:09:37,502 --> 00:09:39,523
that will be look for this object

200
00:09:39,824 --> 00:09:41,885
and then go near this item and take it.

201
00:09:44,500 --> 00:09:46,041
And that's where we're actually going to do

202
00:09:46,102 --> 00:09:47,663
our grounding for the object.

203
00:09:48,403 --> 00:09:50,545
So the look for action, we try to understand

204
00:09:51,145 --> 00:09:55,128
to which object it is the closest to inside the AI memory.

205
00:09:56,249 --> 00:09:58,811
And to do so, we are going to use again a utility-based

206
00:09:58,891 --> 00:10:02,093
system, it's going to be the NPMT-AXIS utility system.

207
00:10:03,675 --> 00:10:05,336
So what I didn't say earlier is that

208
00:10:05,656 --> 00:10:07,137
goals can actually have targets.

209
00:10:07,477 --> 00:10:10,900
So you can have multiple goals with different targets

210
00:10:11,680 --> 00:10:12,921
and compute a score for each of them.

211
00:10:14,102 --> 00:10:16,163
And that's what we are going to do for the look for action.

212
00:10:16,703 --> 00:10:19,524
We are going to have one goal, find suitable objects,

213
00:10:20,845 --> 00:10:21,925
and plenty of targets.

214
00:10:22,445 --> 00:10:25,747
And these targets are going to be the items that my AI knows.

215
00:10:27,007 --> 00:10:28,708
And we're going to compute a score for each of them.

216
00:10:31,129 --> 00:10:35,250
So now we are going to try to understand how close or similar

217
00:10:35,570 --> 00:10:37,931
is this target against the object

218
00:10:37,951 --> 00:10:41,413
that we have in our statement, which was our enormous apple.

219
00:10:43,242 --> 00:10:44,984
So it will depend on different axis.

220
00:10:45,364 --> 00:10:46,746
The first one is object type.

221
00:10:47,066 --> 00:10:49,449
So we are going to compare how close the type of target

222
00:10:49,589 --> 00:10:50,850
and this object DNA is.

223
00:10:52,171 --> 00:10:54,554
And then the size and a lot of different axis,

224
00:10:54,594 --> 00:10:57,197
such as color, location, closeness, and confidence.

225
00:10:58,658 --> 00:11:01,181
We are going to have a weight, a score for each of them,

226
00:11:01,281 --> 00:11:03,543
and combining the score, and we get the score for target.

227
00:11:06,206 --> 00:11:08,448
So let's move into our object type axis

228
00:11:08,528 --> 00:11:11,630
and understand how we can compare the type of this apple,

229
00:11:11,670 --> 00:11:14,172
for instance, against our object DNA.

230
00:11:15,092 --> 00:11:18,375
What we can do is just compute the DNA of apple

231
00:11:18,695 --> 00:11:20,296
and compare both DNA together.

232
00:11:21,277 --> 00:11:22,818
In this case, we have the same DNA,

233
00:11:22,878 --> 00:11:24,319
so we are going to have a score of one.

234
00:11:25,320 --> 00:11:28,042
And for benign tables, the DNA is totally different,

235
00:11:28,222 --> 00:11:29,203
so the score will be zero.

236
00:11:30,495 --> 00:11:35,960
I don't know if you see it now, but we're looking for an enormous apple, which is an edible fruit.

237
00:11:36,520 --> 00:11:41,064
Nevertheless, the score of banana and table are the same, really far away.

238
00:11:41,644 --> 00:11:44,647
But banana is a fruit as well, an edible fruit.

239
00:11:45,507 --> 00:11:50,411
So it would be better to have a better score than zero, but maybe not one, because it's a UTT system.

240
00:11:51,772 --> 00:11:53,614
So we have actually a better way to do so.

241
00:11:54,595 --> 00:11:58,478
WordNet organizes all these things or meanings into a hierarchy.

242
00:12:00,027 --> 00:12:02,989
And our object apple is actually going to be located

243
00:12:03,049 --> 00:12:05,251
right there, below edible fruit.

244
00:12:06,753 --> 00:12:09,455
Which is also the case of banana, but not table,

245
00:12:09,635 --> 00:12:11,577
which is located quite high in the hierarchy.

246
00:12:12,518 --> 00:12:14,740
So we can see how we can get a better score here.

247
00:12:17,242 --> 00:12:20,245
So at first we are going to check where our object DNA

248
00:12:20,345 --> 00:12:23,448
is located inside this hierarchy, and set the node to one,

249
00:12:24,028 --> 00:12:25,609
and just interpolate into the root.

250
00:12:27,806 --> 00:12:30,268
And all the nodes below, because they are also apples,

251
00:12:30,328 --> 00:12:31,329
are going to be set to 1.

252
00:12:33,130 --> 00:12:36,092
And now we can compute a score for all the different objects

253
00:12:36,132 --> 00:12:36,493
we have.

254
00:12:37,654 --> 00:12:40,316
So apple is going to be 1, but banana is going to be,

255
00:12:40,376 --> 00:12:40,736
this time, 0.86.

256
00:12:40,776 --> 00:12:41,517
And table is going to be 0.14.

