00:12:46,018 --> 00:12:47,379
So now we have a better score.

258
00:12:47,880 --> 00:12:51,122
And for instance, if in my game there is no apple,

259
00:12:51,422 --> 00:12:53,443
and I say pick up an enormous apple,

260
00:12:54,224 --> 00:12:57,086
maybe the agent will actually take a banana instead.

261
00:12:57,246 --> 00:12:59,127
But it's still close enough and acceptable.

262
00:12:59,548 --> 00:13:00,868
It's better than a table, right?

263
00:13:04,871 --> 00:13:07,413
Okay, so let's take an example this time

264
00:13:07,553 --> 00:13:10,435
with our apple A, and try to score it.

265
00:13:11,235 --> 00:13:12,856
So the type is the same,

266
00:13:12,917 --> 00:13:14,277
so we are going to have a score of one.

267
00:13:15,154 --> 00:13:18,097
And then for the size, we are going to check our AI memory.

268
00:13:18,597 --> 00:13:21,760
How big is this apple against the thing I know?

269
00:13:22,400 --> 00:13:25,223
It's average in size, so we are going to have a score of 0.5.

270
00:13:26,124 --> 00:13:27,725
And we do the same for the other axis,

271
00:13:27,905 --> 00:13:30,788
and we get a score of 0.91 for apple A.

272
00:13:32,469 --> 00:13:34,351
We do this for all the different items,

273
00:13:34,671 --> 00:13:38,174
and the winner in this case is apple B, our biggest

274
00:13:38,334 --> 00:13:40,996
apple inside the memory, which is what we wanted.

275
00:13:43,676 --> 00:13:45,577
Okay, so the look for action has found

276
00:13:45,617 --> 00:13:49,459
that the closest item inside the AI memory is Applebee.

277
00:13:49,959 --> 00:13:52,701
So now we are just going nearby this item and take it.

278
00:13:53,461 --> 00:13:58,684
And that's what I am going to show you inside this video,

279
00:13:59,344 --> 00:14:00,525
but with different objects.

280
00:14:00,885 --> 00:14:02,146
It's going to be an orange clip.

281
00:14:03,026 --> 00:14:05,928
And because from now on, we are going to talk about emotions,

282
00:14:06,488 --> 00:14:08,209
you will also see some new things,

283
00:14:08,249 --> 00:14:11,050
such as emotional reactions with liking,

284
00:14:11,090 --> 00:14:12,111
disliking behaviors.

285
00:14:14,534 --> 00:14:15,374
Take the orange clip.

286
00:14:21,175 --> 00:14:22,896
Sorry.

287
00:14:22,976 --> 00:14:24,216
Please, take it.

288
00:14:24,236 --> 00:14:28,137
You don't want to take it, right?

289
00:14:28,157 --> 00:14:30,197
I will remove electricity then.

290
00:14:32,978 --> 00:14:36,039
And now, can you take the orange clip?

291
00:14:39,159 --> 00:14:39,459
Great.

292
00:14:39,759 --> 00:14:41,040
You are willing to take it this time.

293
00:14:42,422 --> 00:14:44,503
Can you plug it to the red pole, please?

294
00:14:50,624 --> 00:14:50,905
Cool.

295
00:14:53,445 --> 00:14:56,566
So the goal of this experience was to fix the rocket,

296
00:14:56,826 --> 00:14:58,827
and by plugging the cable to the red pole,

297
00:14:58,867 --> 00:15:00,147
we fixed half of it.

298
00:15:00,267 --> 00:15:02,148
That's why the agent was happy at the end.

299
00:15:02,788 --> 00:15:04,788
But earlier, he has been shocked by the cable,

300
00:15:04,808 --> 00:15:06,429
so he was not really liking it at all.

301
00:15:06,769 --> 00:15:08,970
But at the end, he was maybe starting to like it.

302
00:15:10,005 --> 00:15:12,266
So I will explain this in the next part.

303
00:15:12,426 --> 00:15:15,487
But before, let me introduce our emotional components.

304
00:15:16,628 --> 00:15:18,369
So it's composed of three different modules.

305
00:15:18,729 --> 00:15:21,970
The first one is emotion, so a very short-term feeling

306
00:15:22,110 --> 00:15:24,631
that evolves quickly over time, such as joy, distress,

307
00:15:24,671 --> 00:15:25,011
and fear.

308
00:15:27,072 --> 00:15:28,633
And we have also a mood module, which

309
00:15:28,733 --> 00:15:31,534
is a much more long-term feeling that

310
00:15:31,594 --> 00:15:36,216
evolves slowly and smoothly over time, like exuberant, depressed,

311
00:15:36,336 --> 00:15:36,756
and afraid.

312
00:15:38,521 --> 00:15:39,921
and they are going to influence each other.

313
00:15:42,322 --> 00:15:43,483
And on top of these two module,

314
00:15:43,523 --> 00:15:48,085
we have a personality module that will define the agent.

315
00:15:49,305 --> 00:15:51,246
That has no real evolution over time,

316
00:15:51,546 --> 00:15:54,527
and it's things such as curiosity, shyness, and laziness.

317
00:15:56,428 --> 00:15:58,708
So let's go in our emotion module at first.

318
00:15:59,249 --> 00:16:01,870
So this is an inspired OCC model.

319
00:16:02,110 --> 00:16:03,210
It's not the original one,

320
00:16:03,710 --> 00:16:05,411
but it may still look a bit complex.

321
00:16:06,011 --> 00:16:06,791
So I will explain it.

322
00:16:08,018 --> 00:16:11,342
So it's taking as a top a valence reaction or an event,

323
00:16:12,303 --> 00:16:14,885
and we just assess from our AI point of view

324
00:16:15,146 --> 00:16:17,568
if it's a positive thing or a negative thing.

325
00:16:18,949 --> 00:16:20,671
And then, depending on the type of event,

326
00:16:21,011 --> 00:16:22,373
like an aspect of object,

327
00:16:23,073 --> 00:16:24,995
if I saw something in the world, for instance,

328
00:16:25,876 --> 00:16:27,197
I may like it or dislike it.

329
00:16:27,718 --> 00:16:30,561
Therefore, I will generate a love or hate emotion.

330
00:16:32,345 --> 00:16:35,145
If this event is a consequence of something

331
00:16:35,186 --> 00:16:38,046
that happened in the world, or a consequence of an action,

332
00:16:38,786 --> 00:16:40,287
we may express joy or distress.

333
00:16:41,967 --> 00:16:43,968
And if this event is an action of an agent,

334
00:16:44,188 --> 00:16:48,129
if it's my own actions, I'm going to express pride or shame,

335
00:16:49,249 --> 00:16:51,350
and if it's the action of the player, for instance,

336
00:16:51,590 --> 00:16:54,651
I may express admiration or reproach towards the player.

337
00:16:56,183 --> 00:16:59,924
And also, if there is a related consequence to these actions,

338
00:17:00,344 --> 00:17:02,665
if it's a related consequence to my own actions,

339
00:17:02,825 --> 00:17:05,546
I'm going to express them to be gratification or remorse.

340
00:17:06,386 --> 00:17:07,807
And if it's a related consequence

341
00:17:07,827 --> 00:17:10,488
to the action of the player, I may express gratitude

342
00:17:10,628 --> 00:17:11,708
or anger toward him.

343
00:17:13,783 --> 00:17:17,045
So that's the model, it may even still be complex.

344
00:17:17,325 --> 00:17:18,425
So let's take an example.

345
00:17:18,885 --> 00:17:21,946
So earlier in this video, the agent has been shocked

346
00:17:21,986 --> 00:17:25,387
by the cable, and this cable was activated by the player.

347
00:17:25,807 --> 00:17:27,088
Yes, press the button, right?

348
00:17:28,628 --> 00:17:32,069
So this event is negative for our agent, I think, right?

349
00:17:34,930 --> 00:17:36,831
It was a consequence of the event,

350
00:17:37,471 --> 00:17:40,092
of the action of the player, activation of the button.

351
00:17:41,621 --> 00:17:43,862
So we are going to express our distressed emotion.

352
00:17:43,902 --> 00:17:45,603
We are not really happy that we have been shocked

353
00:17:45,623 --> 00:17:46,203
by the cable.

354
00:17:47,503 --> 00:17:50,484
But we are also going to express anger towards the player

355
00:17:50,625 --> 00:17:52,685
because it's his fault that I have been shocked

356
00:17:53,045 --> 00:17:53,686
by this cable.

357
00:17:54,786 --> 00:17:57,207
And that's how we are going to generate our emotions.

358
00:17:59,328 --> 00:18:03,130
So now, how can we like or dislike the thing in the walls?

359
00:18:04,450 --> 00:18:08,512
Well, earlier, when the agent has been shocked by the cable,

360
00:18:08,772 --> 00:18:10,753
we have generated our distressed emotions.

361
00:18:11,587 --> 00:18:13,669
But you can do one more thing at this step.

362
00:18:14,790 --> 00:18:18,755
We can also add a negative effect to the cable object,

363
00:18:18,995 --> 00:18:21,197
but also to the electrified predicate.

364
00:18:22,299 --> 00:18:24,441
And an effect will just be an intensity

365
00:18:24,781 --> 00:18:28,065
with a memorable duration, so that it can forget over time.

366
00:18:29,927 --> 00:18:32,089
And now, thanks to this effect.

367
00:18:32,987 --> 00:18:35,348
The agent will not like anything that is a cable

368
00:18:35,549 --> 00:18:37,109
or anything that is electrified.

369
00:18:37,570 --> 00:18:40,111
So if there is another electrified something over there,

370
00:18:40,311 --> 00:18:41,451
it will not get close to it.

371
00:18:43,953 --> 00:18:44,393
So great.

372
00:18:45,173 --> 00:18:47,535
The agent does not like the electrified cable anymore.

373
00:18:48,075 --> 00:18:49,776
So what if we tell him to take it again?

374
00:18:51,677 --> 00:18:53,017
Well, the plan is still the same.

375
00:18:53,457 --> 00:18:55,118
We're still going to look for our cable.

376
00:18:56,279 --> 00:18:57,900
We are going to find it, and then we

377
00:18:57,920 --> 00:18:59,900
are going to try to go nearby this cable.

378
00:19:00,180 --> 00:19:02,461
But because he's hating it, he will refuse,

379
00:19:02,881 --> 00:19:04,102
and the plan will be canceled.

380
00:19:06,583 --> 00:19:08,243
OK, next, the mood.

381
00:19:09,004 --> 00:19:14,106
So it is based on the PAD model, so pleasure, arousal, dominance.

382
00:19:15,126 --> 00:19:17,907
And the P means how pleasant is an emotion.

383
00:19:18,947 --> 00:19:21,588
A is about how intense is an emotion.

384
00:19:22,597 --> 00:19:26,778
And D, a bit more complex, it's about how much control

385
00:19:26,978 --> 00:19:29,739
and influence the agent has over situations.

386
00:19:31,919 --> 00:19:34,700
And inside this cube, we'll have all of our emotions.

387
00:19:36,461 --> 00:19:39,181
And this cube can be separated into eight octants.

388
00:19:39,682 --> 00:19:41,342
For instance, here we have the mood afraid.

389
00:19:42,743 --> 00:19:44,763
And at the top right, where joy is,

390
00:19:44,843 --> 00:19:46,304
it's going to be the mood exuberant.

391
00:19:46,704 --> 00:19:47,704
So we have eight of them.

392
00:19:49,573 --> 00:19:52,655
And inside this cube, we have our default mood,

393
00:19:52,975 --> 00:19:54,336
which is currently at the position 0, 0, 0.

394
00:19:56,717 --> 00:20:00,019
And this mood is going to move smoothly over time,

395
00:20:00,139 --> 00:20:02,820
depending on what emotions are going to be generated.

396
00:20:05,141 --> 00:20:06,562
So let's see the update now.

397
00:20:07,222 --> 00:20:08,783
So let's say we have a joy emotion

398
00:20:08,863 --> 00:20:11,244
with a certain intensity for five seconds.

399
00:20:12,285 --> 00:20:14,266
Depending on the intensity, the speed

400
00:20:14,346 --> 00:20:17,007
at which the dot will move towards the joy emotion

401
00:20:17,467 --> 00:20:18,148
will be different.

402
00:20:19,327 --> 00:20:20,808
And when the emotion has been expressed,

403
00:20:21,008 --> 00:20:22,890
there is no emotional activity anymore.

404
00:20:23,450 --> 00:20:26,632
So we will slowly go back to our default mood.

405
00:20:28,633 --> 00:20:32,076
In a more complex example, it can be something like that.

406
00:20:34,297 --> 00:20:35,698
So here we are exuberant,

407
00:20:35,978 --> 00:20:37,959
and even more exuberant right now.

408
00:20:37,999 --> 00:20:40,841
We can see that he's very smiley now.

409
00:20:42,742 --> 00:20:44,223
And now a bit of eight,

410
00:20:44,263 --> 00:20:46,865
so we are just in the hostile mood just at the beginning,

411
00:20:47,065 --> 00:20:48,806
and we can see a sort of vicious smile.

412
00:20:49,604 --> 00:20:51,225
Now he's quite not happy at all.

413
00:20:52,285 --> 00:20:56,147
And now due to the same emotion, he's very sad, a bit afraid.

414
00:20:59,569 --> 00:21:01,369
And now a very strong hate emotion,

415
00:21:01,429 --> 00:21:02,910
and we can see that he's very not happy.

416
00:21:04,771 --> 00:21:07,012
So thanks to this PID model, now we

417
00:21:07,032 --> 00:21:09,053
are able to blend our different animation

418
00:21:09,113 --> 00:21:11,814
for the different moods and get some new things,

419
00:21:11,854 --> 00:21:14,455
such as the vicious smile.

420
00:21:16,116 --> 00:21:17,316
So it's a very powerful tool.

421
00:21:20,158 --> 00:21:22,099
And lastly, we have our personality module,

422
00:21:22,539 --> 00:21:23,819
which is the simplest one.

423
00:21:24,579 --> 00:21:27,280
It's just UTT parameters, such as laziness,

424
00:21:27,380 --> 00:21:29,221
curiosity, honesty, obedience.

425
00:21:31,061 --> 00:21:32,841
And I want to introduce at first

426
00:21:33,442 --> 00:21:34,962
how we have done the laziness one.

427
00:21:35,942 --> 00:21:38,843
So in this video, at first, yes, laziness is 10%,

428
00:21:39,243 --> 00:21:40,343
so not very lazy.

429
00:21:41,323 --> 00:21:41,904
So let's check.

430
00:21:42,204 --> 00:21:43,664
Take the purple clip, please.

431
00:21:47,074 --> 00:21:49,036
So here, yes, he's just going to take the purple clip.

432
00:21:49,236 --> 00:21:49,976
Nothing special.

433
00:21:49,996 --> 00:21:56,281
Take the purple clip, please.

434
00:21:57,882 --> 00:21:58,943
But now he's very lazy.

435
00:21:59,223 --> 00:22:01,205
He does not care anymore about the color

436
00:22:01,225 --> 00:22:01,945
or any other thing.

437
00:22:02,105 --> 00:22:04,227
He just want to take the clip, the closest one,

438
00:22:05,128 --> 00:22:05,988
because he's very lazy.

439
00:22:08,170 --> 00:22:09,351
So how did we do that?

440
00:22:10,493 --> 00:22:12,775
So personality laziness parameter

441
00:22:12,995 --> 00:22:15,277
is going to affect our look for action.

442
00:22:15,577 --> 00:22:18,579
We'll favor closer object over farther object.

443
00:22:20,741 --> 00:22:22,022
If you remember earlier,

444
00:22:22,042 --> 00:22:26,025
I introduced our find suitable object action

445
00:22:26,085 --> 00:22:28,146
with a certain axis named closeness.

446
00:22:28,746 --> 00:22:31,769
And you can see that the weight is 0.1, so very small.

447
00:22:32,549 --> 00:22:34,130
So maybe why is it small?

448
00:22:34,210 --> 00:22:35,351
Maybe that's the first question.

449
00:22:36,248 --> 00:22:39,530
Well, we just wanted, just in case we have two items

450
00:22:39,590 --> 00:22:42,931
with the same score, we wanted to favorite the item

451
00:22:42,971 --> 00:22:46,173
that is a bit closer to the agent, but just a little bit.

452
00:22:47,214 --> 00:22:50,615
But in this case, the lazier the agent is,

453
00:22:51,016 --> 00:22:53,537
the more important the closeness axis should be.

454
00:22:54,257 --> 00:22:56,158
So instead of having a static weight,

455
00:22:56,859 --> 00:22:58,600
we are going to have actually a way

456
00:22:58,640 --> 00:23:00,921
that will depend on this laziness axis.

457
00:23:01,701 --> 00:23:03,242
And we can add a range if we want.

458
00:23:04,719 --> 00:23:08,040
And thanks to this, we are now able to express our laziness

459
00:23:08,440 --> 00:23:09,541
personality parameter.

460
00:23:13,342 --> 00:23:15,742
In general, the personality parameters

461
00:23:15,762 --> 00:23:18,303
can affect a lot of different things in the decision making.

462
00:23:18,563 --> 00:23:20,644
They can affect your goal manager, goal score,

463
00:23:20,804 --> 00:23:23,045
or the set of actions you will use for the planner.

464
00:23:23,585 --> 00:23:26,506
They can affect also the tolerance on liking, disliking,

465
00:23:27,426 --> 00:23:30,407
or the way the emotions are going to be expressed.

466
00:23:30,567 --> 00:23:31,727
For instance, with shyness.

467
00:23:33,130 --> 00:23:35,913
So it's a very powerful tool, despite being very simple.

468
00:23:36,653 --> 00:23:38,755
And it allows for a great variation of place.

469
00:23:39,195 --> 00:23:40,676
And if we have multiple NPCs,

470
00:23:40,716 --> 00:23:42,878
they will all feel a bit different to each other.

471
00:23:45,520 --> 00:23:47,642
Okay, so lastly I would like to talk about

472
00:23:47,662 --> 00:23:51,265
a factual statement, which is about

473
00:23:51,405 --> 00:23:53,266
informing the agent about the world.

474
00:23:55,888 --> 00:23:57,770
Maybe there is a nozzle in front of the rocket.

475
00:24:00,412 --> 00:24:01,193
Can you take the nozzle?

476
00:24:05,024 --> 00:24:07,425
So here he's looking around in front of the rocket.

477
00:24:10,027 --> 00:24:11,548
And he found the nozzle, very happy.

478
00:24:15,210 --> 00:24:17,131
Maybe there is another in front of the rocket.

479
00:24:20,313 --> 00:24:21,213
Can you take the nozzle?

480
00:24:22,254 --> 00:24:23,975
So obviously here there is no nozzle,

481
00:24:24,275 --> 00:24:26,756
but he's still going to look for it in front of the rocket.

482
00:24:28,978 --> 00:24:29,758
But yeah, this time.

483
00:24:30,555 --> 00:24:31,555
There is no nozzle, right?

484
00:24:31,755 --> 00:24:33,857
There is no nozzle, so he's not really happy about it.

485
00:24:34,137 --> 00:24:35,998
We lied to him, so he's not very happy.

486
00:24:37,879 --> 00:24:38,960
So how did we do that?

487
00:24:40,240 --> 00:24:42,402
Well, at first, the player is just going to say a statement,

488
00:24:42,722 --> 00:24:44,963
such as, there is an apple on the table.

489
00:24:45,984 --> 00:24:47,725
So we are going to listen to the statement,

490
00:24:48,085 --> 00:24:51,127
and we are going to create a factual apple in our memory.

491
00:24:51,427 --> 00:24:53,388
We don't know yet if it's actually existing.

492
00:24:55,089 --> 00:24:57,951
And then the player is asking the agent to take an apple.

493
00:24:59,432 --> 00:25:02,154
So we'll look for action, we find that the best object

494
00:25:02,374 --> 00:25:04,695
is this factual object, this factual apple.

495
00:25:05,715 --> 00:25:08,377
But we don't know yet if it's actually existing in the world

496
00:25:08,557 --> 00:25:10,438
so we are going to try to ground it.

497
00:25:14,840 --> 00:25:16,121
So another goal we'll take over

498
00:25:16,741 --> 00:25:18,282
is going to be the ground fact goal

499
00:25:18,662 --> 00:25:20,323
and the goal will be to go on the table

500
00:25:20,603 --> 00:25:21,563
and just look around.

501
00:25:22,124 --> 00:25:23,304
In this case there is an apple

502
00:25:23,444 --> 00:25:25,685
so we're just going to replace our factual apple

503
00:25:26,045 --> 00:25:26,706
with this apple.

504
00:25:28,204 --> 00:25:30,106
So when the takeApple action will take over,

505
00:25:30,586 --> 00:25:31,787
we'll find the correct apple

506
00:25:31,867 --> 00:25:33,449
and the agent will be happy about it.

507
00:25:40,094 --> 00:25:42,076
So what if there is no apple on the table?

508
00:25:42,477 --> 00:25:45,619
Well, the ground fact action still, goal still happen.

509
00:25:46,200 --> 00:25:48,222
We're still going to go on the table,

510
00:25:48,522 --> 00:25:49,983
but we're going to find no apple.

511
00:25:50,003 --> 00:25:51,685
So we just remove the factual object.

512
00:25:52,585 --> 00:25:54,847
